crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature detects an Adobe Type 1 Font. The Type 1 Font Format is a standardized font format for digital imaging applications.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: InQuest Labs

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis:
While an internal technical analysis of the PDF's structure did not find conclusive evidence of maliciousness, it did identify suspicious components, including a JavaScript object and an object containing a URI. The technical report could not establish an execution chain or determine the purpose of these objects due to missing data and a lack of automatic triggers, leading to its benign classification.

However, analysis of the visual layer provides critical context that resolves this ambiguity. The document displays a deceptive pop-up that impersonates an official Adobe Acrobat software update notification. This pop-up is overlaid on a seemingly legitimate government document and uses social engineering tactics, such as urgency cues ("out of date", "has been blocked"), to pressure the user into clicking a prominent "Update" button.

Synthesizing these findings, the visual evidence confirms a malicious intent. The JavaScript and URI objects identified in the technical report are almost certainly linked to the fake update button. The document's purpose is to act as a phishing lure, tricking the user into clicking the button, which would likely lead to malware execution or redirection to a malicious website.
